    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-06-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-06-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="88"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d88">
                <head>88. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RWP1" type="from"
                        >Rogers</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to"
                        >Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d88fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, President’s Evening Reading: Lot 74
                            <gloss target="#t_D1">D</gloss> 164.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d88fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> reported that the Department
                        of State had introduced a resolution in the <gloss target="#t_ICAO1"
                            >ICAO</gloss> calling for a resumption of work on an international
                        convention to provide sanctions against governments that aided
                        hijackers.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1972-06-15"
                        >June 15, 1972</date>.</dateline>
                <p>MEMORANDUM FOR THE PRESIDENT - Evening Report</p>
                <p>1. <hi rend="underline">United States Action in International Civil Aviation
                        Organization Regarding Aviation Security</hi> - In view of the Lod Airport
                    massacre in Tel Aviv and the recent hijacking of a U.S. aircraft to Algeria, the
                    United States has introduced a resolution in the Council of the International
                    Civil Aviation Organization (<gloss target="#t_ICAO1">ICAO</gloss>) calling for
                    the resumption of work on an international convention to provide for sanctions
                    against Governments which fail to prosecute or extradite hijackers. This
                    resolution will be considered by the <gloss target="#t_ICAO1">ICAO</gloss>
                    Council on June 16. Although only last month the Legal Committee of <gloss
                        target="#t_ICAO1">ICAO</gloss> voted to suspend work on a sanctions
                    convention, our Embassies in most of the other <gloss target="#t_ICAO1"
                        >ICAO</gloss> Council member States, including the <gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                        >USSR</gloss>, are endeavoring at high levels to obtain support for our
                    proposal. We are hopeful that the recent incidents will spur sufficient support
                    for our proposal to be adopted tomorrow. We are also making efforts to obtain a
                    consensus statement at the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Security Council
                    which would back up our efforts in <gloss target="#t_ICAO1">ICAO</gloss>.</p>
                <p>The International Federation of Airline Pilots Association has called for a
                    strike on June 19 unless in the meantime action has been taken by the <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_ICAO1">ICAO</gloss> on
                    aviation security.</p>
                <p>We are continuing to press the Algerians to prosecute the hijackers and return
                    the ransom money from the recent Western Airlines hijacking.</p>
                <p rend="center">[Omitted here are two paragraphs unrelated to Global Issues]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">William P. Rogers</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
